## Scrum Poker web app — V1 plan & hosting notes

### Goal (V1)
Build a simple, robust real-time Scrum Poker web app:
- Create a room on the website
- Share a link
- Others join the same room
- Everyone votes (hidden), then reveal + reset rounds

### Core V1 features
- Create room → unique room id + share URL
- Join room → enter display name (no accounts/passwords in V1)
- Presence → show who is in the room (with reconnect tolerance)
- Voting round:
  - pick a card (vote hidden until reveal)
  - show “X votes submitted” (optional)
  - moderator can Reveal + Reset (next round)
- Optional: topic/issue label per round

### Simple roles
- Room creator becomes moderator
- If moderator leaves: assign a new moderator (first/next participant)

### Recommended tech stack (VPS-friendly, Python-first)
- Backend + pages: Python + Flask
- Templates: Jinja2 (Flask templates)
- Realtime: WebSockets via Flask-SocketIO (Socket.IO semantics, Python server)
- Database: PostgreSQL (recommended for public/unknown users)
- Reverse proxy (VPS): Nginx for HTTPS + WebSocket proxying
- Process management (VPS): systemd
- Optional for scaling beyond 1 process: Redis (Socket.IO message queue)

### System overview
- Browsers load HTML via HTTPS (server-rendered templates)
- Browser JS connects to Socket.IO endpoint for realtime updates
- Server is source of truth (clients can’t “reveal” by themselves)
- Server stores votes hidden until reveal event
- After reveal, server emits revealed results to the room

### Data model (minimal)
- rooms: id, created_at, last_active_at, state (voting/revealed), round_number, current_topic, moderator_participant_id
- participants: id, room_id, display_name, joined_at, last_seen_at
- votes: room_id, participant_id, value, round_number

### Robustness requirements (still V1)
- Reconnect handling:
  - store participant_id in secure session cookie
  - on reconnect, map socket to existing participant
  - use last_seen_at for presence tolerance (e.g. consider “present” if seen in last 60s)
- Basic validation + rate limiting (HTTP routes + socket events)
- Room expiration (auto-delete inactive rooms after N hours/days)
- Keep DB/app region in EU

### Hosting conclusions
- Traditional shared hosting is usually NOT suitable for WebSockets.
- Use a VPS or a managed app platform that explicitly supports WebSockets.
- You can still use your own .nl domain and point it to where the app runs.

### EU/EER “on European soil”
- Choose EU region for both app + database (and ideally backups/logs too).

### TransIP notes (deployment target)
- TransIP can host both domain + DNS, and you can run the app on their VPS.
- Minimal VPS suggestion for V1:
  - 1 vCPU, 1 GB RAM for small usage
  - Prefer 2 GB RAM if running Postgres on the same VPS
- Reliability baseline for public users:
  - systemd auto-restart for app process
  - off-VPS Postgres backups (at least daily)
  - basic uptime monitoring
  - firewall + security updates

### Local development plan (now)
- Install: Python 3.12+ (or your preferred), Git, (optional) Docker Desktop
- Run Postgres locally (Docker or native)
- Use env vars via `.env` in dev; later systemd env on VPS
- Build V1 with Flask + Jinja + Flask-SocketIO + Postgres

### Build plan (step-by-step)
1) Define V1 scope (must-have vs nice-to-have)
2) Create project skeleton:
   - app/ (Flask app)
   - templates/ (Jinja pages)
   - static/ (minimal JS + CSS)
3) Add dependencies:
   - Flask, Flask-SocketIO
   - Postgres driver + DB layer (SQLAlchemy or plain SQL)
4) Add Postgres locally and create minimal schema (rooms, participants, votes)
5) Implement HTTP pages:
   - GET / (create room)
   - POST /rooms (create room + creator becomes moderator)
   - GET /r/<room_id> (room page; join prompt or room UI)
   - POST /r/<room_id>/join (set display name + session cookie)
6) Implement Socket.IO event protocol:
   - Client→Server: join_room, vote, reveal, reset, set_topic(optional)
   - Server→Client: room_state (authoritative snapshot), error
   - Rule: before reveal, never send vote values (only has_voted/count)
7) Identity + reconnect:
   - store participant_id in secure cookie session
   - map socket connection to participant on connect
8) Presence:
   - update last_seen_at on connect/ping/events
   - show present participants (recent last_seen_at)
9) Public-safety minimums:
   - rate limiting (create/join/vote; socket events too)
   - input validation for names/topic/votes
   - moderator-only authorization for reveal/reset
   - room expiration cleanup
10) Test locally end-to-end:
   - create room → multi-browser join → vote → reveal → reset → refresh/reconnect
11) Deploy to TransIP VPS:
   - Nginx (HTTPS + WebSocket upgrade proxy)
   - run app under systemd
   - Postgres on VPS (or later migrate to managed Postgres)
   - automated backups + monitoring

### Open decisions to confirm later
- Subdomain (recommended): poker.yourdomain.nl or scrumpoker.yourdomain.nl vs main domain
- DB approach for V1:
  - Self-host Postgres on the VPS (cheapest) + solid backups
  - or managed Postgres (less maintenance)
- Scaling:
  - single app process (V1) vs multiple workers (requires Redis message queue for Socket.IO)